{[show S]After a 1NT opening, the partnership uses Stayman to ask whether opener holds a four-card major before settling the contract. When no fit comes back, the right home is usually notrump.
[BID 1N] You have 15-17 with a balanced hand, so open 1NT and describe the whole hand in one bid. That lets partner take charge of placing the contract. Your partner uses 2\C as Stayman, asking opener for a four-card major. It says nothing about clubs and promises enough strength to act on the answer.
[BID 2D] You have no four-card major, so bid 2\D as the standard Stayman denial. It steers the auction back toward notrump. Your partner hears the 2\D denial and, with no major fit and game values, raises straight to 3NT. With the combined count for game and no eight-card major, notrump is the place to play.
[BID Pass] You pass; 3NT is the final contract.
[show NS]North's Stayman ran into a 2\D denial, so the partnership wisely landed in 3NT. South opened a balanced 1NT with \SK2 \HJT8 \DAK64 \CAJ96, and the strong diamonds and clubs gave declarer the tricks to bring home nine.}
[Note "1:Stayman"]
